Scene X - Texel:
Version A:
==========
Abandoned, dangerous potentially with homeless people. The Templers - 150 years old German neighborhood - part of the complicated history of Jerusalem.
I am 30. She is 23 years old and was released from the army a couple of years before with her highly intelligent trained dog 'Texel'.
The bond between the human to the dog is so deep, that although the dog is military property, it isn't past to the next soldier, but is released into civilian life with the soldier. He is sweet and intelligent, but also able to attack. The woman would give the dog commands: " sit, come, scan". They have a whole system of communication. Once arriving at a location with the sought for ammunition scent, the dog would sit and wage its tail and receive a treat.
I loved going into those houses, visiting an old past. 
Part of the neighborhood was renovated into expensive houses, and some deserted.
This day we ventured into a big deserted school with a vast schoolyard. 
The staircase was loose, so we climbed up near the wall, where the structure is strongest.
This reminds me of the way, one goes to the staircase, in old structures with no shelter, during a bombing.

We went two flights up, where there was a balcony with no railing, only a step at the height of the knees. The dog runs and hopes up to the banister. I arrive just in time to see him scrambling trying to stay on the step, just like in a cartoon movie, where the animal’s legs are running without traction in the air. Then he fell. The girl arrives calling for the dog. She is hysterical. I tried to keep her away from the edge. We go down the stairs very slow.

She is crying and shouting "Shit Shit Texel Texel". I realize she is loosing it and hysterical. I fear that she might fall too down the stairs, so I hold her tight. We very slowly exit the building. I run to where the dog is lying, on its side, crying, and breathing fast short breaths. I pet it and call the girl to us.
She is crying. There is dried straw around us (it is summer).
I say move back I'm a medic, I'll check it. You know what - stay here with the dog, I'll go get help. I run to the fence we've jumped over to enter the closed compound. I yell back" Where is the vet?"" She answers the address. I realize that it's best that she runs to get the vet and I stay with the dog.
I feel guilty - that it's my fault this happened - The dog is here because of me. It's my crazy hobby. I am petting and talking to the dog: "I'm sorry". The dog only breaths fast short breaths back.
I think - ' this is my specialty - taking care of trauma'. So I tell it " Don't worry - you'll be fine ", just like I am supposed to talk to any patient in order to keep him conscience. I do the basic survey of medical situation, just as the medical protocol orders: check pulse, check under all the body parts to see if there is any lose of blood. I find blood near its tail. I go over all the body, down the back, the legs and all the tail. I could feel at two points there were broken bones. I am not a vet, I just did the human parallel/equivalent  to what I'd do on this dog. One of the legs, I think, is broken, and maybe some internal bleeding.
I try to make the dog move the tail (to checks spinal cord functioning / control or reflex). I pick up the tail and let it go. It falls. I pick it up again and let it go. I think I can imagine it moving a bit. But no, it isn't moving at all. This is a bad sign.
She came back and said the vet isn't there. The only vet she knows is in a different neighborhood. She is scared and confused. I help her call a vet but we get only answering machines. Finally there is a vet that answers and says that this weekend (today is Friday afternoon) all the vets are at a convention in Eilat, in the south, and that the place to go for trauma is Rishon Lezion and gave us the number. I think we should stop a cab. I tell her lets search a board for carrying the dog.
We found a table board (from the school). I manage to roll the dog onto the board. We picked it up and passed it over the fence as the cab stops. We ask to enter the dog in the baggage. Luckily the driver agrees and puts down the rear seat of the station wagon cab, to create more space in the baggage. The cab driver is Israeli, dark colored and bearded.

The girl is sits in the front seat crying. I opened the rear door. Just like I'm supposed to do before boarding the helicopter with a patient, I survey the patient’s vital signs. his pulse is ok, but his breathing is so slow it actually stopped. So exactly like in the CPR manual - I gave Texel two deep breaths. I took out his tongue and held it with my hand. It is a wolf dog. I hold it and with my other hand I seal his mouth. I felt his teeth on my teeth.
I exhale two breaths into his mouth and make sure I see his chest going up. I checkhis pulse. I'm not sure I can find it.
I know there is not a lot of time for Texel, but our destination of the vet is only 10 minutes away so we can make it in time for the trauma equipment.The driver helps me load the table into the baggage. I enter the baggage with the board and the dog on it. 
This configuration brings me back to the similar environment in the helicopter. The pilot is in the front flying, and I’m with he injured in the back. It's moving fast and shaking and I’m not stable holding on to the walls, without a seatbelt. The streets of Jerusalem, are steep and curved, so as I kneel on the board in the baggage, and get jerked towards the car roof and sides, all of which is just like in the helicopter.
I check the pulse. I might be imaging that I am feeling a pulse. I yell to the girl "don't worry. We will be fine". As in CPR I’m supposed to give two breaths every 30 seconds.
I count and give a breath, then count and then another one. We keep driving in Jerusalem another five minutes. As i keep giving breaths, I improve my technic of giving air. The problem is that his tongue keeps falling in, and this might cause suffocation. I must hold the tongue out also between breaths. I see his eyes staring at me, and then looking into the space. I pet him.
I shout to her:" Everything is going to be OK"
I shout to the driver"if that station is closed - drive to Ramat Yovel". The vet we arrive at is closed because it's already Shabat. I tell the driver go to the other vet at another address.
I improve my breathing technic. I think I can feel the pulse in his neck.
About ten min. into the drive, I can't feel the pulse any longer. Massive 20 kilo. I look for pulse in the leg. but can't find it. return searching in it's neck, still can't find it. I realize that I must continue CPR until we arrive at the Vet only 15 minutes longer, to keep Texel's body alive. At the vet we will be able to give him electric boost to get the heart pumping again.
CPS is 5 heart contractions and one breath. 5 jolts to his heart and one breath.
I turn/ roll it on it's back, but it rolls to the other side. so I roll t back to the first side, as the taxi driver takes a turn. I find the heart and give it a jolt. I don't tell her anything. It is tiring. I am glad that I’m in good physical shape. I feel I'm succeeding to get in deep breaths. For the first time I fear that he might not make it.
I my rescue missions I was never attached to the outcome. It's been always technical. You do what you can, but at the end, it's just another day at work.
Here, maybe because I felt it is my fault, It’s the dog of my neighbor, I learnt to like and even admire it's talent. I feel the dog saliva all over me. I clean it with my arm, thinking "what the fuck am I doing, this is like kissing a dog". 
The girl keeps crying.
I get tired and am already leaning on my side and giving pumps with one hand.
Slowly Texel began going cold. The air coming out of his lungs onto my face was now cold, his lips too. The muscle tone was relaxed so the body became wobbly.
I distinctly remember us driving up a main street, to Kiryat Yovel.
I was pretty punctual and persistent in administering the jolts and breaths on time. I could feel the dog's soul leaving his body and going out the glass of the rear door up into the sky. I felt it go up and away.

I was determined to keep it alive so I kept on jolting the heart pumps and blowing in more air.
I began crying. It was important for me that I will save him. “Mother fucker don’t die!” Just like in the ER TV show, I was talking to it: "Don't die. don't die".
The girl is in the front crying so can't hear or see my tears, so she isn’t aware of of the situation. We aren’t really communicating. Once in a while she asks for some update on his situation but mostly she is crying getting directions on the phone and directing the driver. I see the girl there but we aren't communicating.
I talk to Texel : "Don't die don't die. We are almost there." while I cry.
Slowly I feel that IT is becoming cold and what I’m doing is actually moving a body. 
At the beginning there was tension in it’s muscles, but now there is no tension at all. I open the mouth without any tension in it. I am now actually blowing my air into meat, into nothing or a dead body. In the beginning of the CPR I’d feel hot air coming out back at me from his lunges, but now coming out of it is only cold air, but still I continue to blow in every 5 counts. I feel that it is becoming cold meat.
 But I feel that it's cold meat. I am actually moving a cold body. Like a schnitzel.
But I've lost control by this point. I continue persistently blowing air into the month. The driver says that we reached the neighborhood and will be arriving at the vet in a couple of minutes. 
I open its eyelids and it's looking into the air. I continue 1,2,3,4,5 breath. 3,4,5 breath. 
We finally arrive at the vet. 
It is too late.

Version B:
He is waiting for us at out in the parking lot. I say hi we have a dog. Please check it. He replies ya ya please come to the clinic. He gets to the clinic door, but it’s shut by it’s automatic door which has no electricity now so it is stuck. 
He said he must have his medical equipment in order to check. I pushed harder: “ you are a vet – come and just check the dog”.
The vet agrees and comes to the trunk.  He agreed and arrived to the trunk and checked the eye dilation and pulse.

Vet: “What height?” “ How much time passed since the fall ?”. “ when did is stop breathing ?
Me:”. Third floor.less than an hour” About 30 minutes ago
He takes me asaid and says: “ listen man I really want to help, but I really don’t think there is much we can do. It’s been more than half an hour without oxygen in the brain”.
ME: I’m doing the human equivalent calculations “ Of course we can do much. We will get the dog to an electric defibulator and give his heart electic shocks to get working again. There is the first golden hour. So if we get him there in the first hour – there is still a good chance.”
The vet is resisting.
I show him: “ look this is the CPR I’m doing on it. Am I doing it ok?”
Vet:” yes, but actually you can do it like this.” 
He tries to get me off this animal, but I convince him to show me how to do CPR correctly to a dog. Now really shows me how to use the fist in order to CPR a dog. He knows the dog is dead but I am persistent. “ 
Vet: “he is dead. But continue doing what you are doing with the fist. Ill drive my car and lea you to the clinic just know that this dog is probably dead.”
Me:” no. I will keep him alive until we get to the next clinic and we will there revive him. Aren’t you a vet? Don’t you sware the Hypocrotus outh? Don’t you want to keep him alive?”
Vet:” yes , but it is Shabat coiming in. Everthing is probably closed now”.
Me: “ no. We will keep him alive and get to the other vet. We already called there and they are open and waiting for us”
Vet:” ok ok . follow my car”
Those next  3-4 minutes I already knew how to apply the right pressure on the heart with my fist, but I am actually working on cold meat. No mussel tension at all. Working with remaining of a body of a og. 
He already asked : 

He says the door is stuck but he will take us to another vet that is nearby. Only three minutes away. I asked him if he wants to check the dog here in the baggage. He replied that there is nothing that he could do without the equipment, so I can just continue the cpr as I’ve done. He will drive in his car and lead the way to the clinic.

We get there. He helps me carry the table top inside with the dog. I ask the second vet to come and check the dog in the baggage, but she asks we bring the dog into her clinic. We carry the wooden table top into the clinic and she checks him with her statoscope.
She checks dialation and heart and says there is nothing we can do.
ME:” let’s give him electric shock to the heart”
VSecond vet:” we don’t even have that here. Nothing to do. Go drink some water and tell us what to do with the body.”
The girl was crying and we sat. I washed the blood and salaiva of my hands and mouth in the toylets. Several days late I still had a stench of dog breath on me.
First Vet: “ Let me know how I can help. There is a dog cemetery near by which costs 200 shekel for a grave. I can give you all their details.”
We sat and drank water. She was crying and calling her mother.
The second vet:”  IT’S SHABES WE HAVE TO CLOST. TELL ME what you want to do with the body. 
 
The first vet:” there is a nive place in nature near my Moshav where you can burry the body for free”.
I got home and brough t my car, we put the dog in the baggage raped in a bed lenen.I brought a shovel from my theater school and drove to the road bend and flash light. And the first vet gave directions to 15 minutes out of Jerusalem, on top of a hill, 
We got there and I looked for a place to burry, but the soil was hard and the shovel didn’t enter.
I was very tired. It was all dark.
I carried the dog on my shoulders down the hill and placed him on the ground near the half dug grave. The shovel wouldn’t go any deeper. I couldn’t possibly carry the dog back up again the hill, and back into the car for a place with better soil. So we decided to leave it there. We gathered stones and rocks and made a pill on the dog’s body. She held the flash light on it. She said a few words about Texel. I said a few words.
We got back to the car. The drive to my parents was quiet. I asked if she wants to come for Friday night dinner at my parents, she arrived and sat there in total shock. My sister tried to talk to her a bit. My dog ‘y’ arrived all cheerful and alive to greet us.
The connetion I had with this animal, after many years of treating death, patients, I never cared for any of them ever. You could have placed there a bag of potatos and it would have benn exactely the same for me. Exactely the same. Very technical and simple. I take it and do the medical procedure nad pass it to the hospital. Not any emotional connection. Didn’t eve remember the names or anything.
For this dog I fought. I really wanted him to make it through. Sudeenly I really fought for 30 min CPR in a moving car. I went into a past situation. Mussel memory.  I relived all those rescues through this dog. I cryed and talked to it and peted it. Only the two of us talking. I really tried to give all I can. This never would have happened before with human patients.
 I remember feeling the soul leaving .it could be my imagination of course but I felt it leaving through the back glass window of the cab. After it left, the body was still warm. Still warm. But I knew what had just happened. It’s gone. 
I cried.
Although I had dozens of those before and I never car.
Maybe because I felt It was my fault. I knew the dog. And cared for the feelings the girl.
The girl said after several days : “ I appreciate all you did for the dog. It was amazing.”
I first didn’t tell her but final admitted :” I didn’t do it for the dog or for you I went through something. “  
Even the vets both looked at me, with a face of “you’ve lost it” “ it’s only a dog . let go!”.
The girl thinks I fought for her.
I was an unfinished business for me to want to save a life.
That detachment isn’t part of the training. You train a lot on dummies. You never invest emotionally. 




Texel –Version C:
One Friday afternoon, at the Jerusalem Templer neighborhood, I met my neighbor to scan though deserted buildings. The whole neighborhood was built from big old Jerusalem stone, 150 years ago, including a church, ministry and school. Some of these buildings were luxuriously renovated for wealthy families, but some left empty and invited seasonal narcotic users, prostitutes or homeless to take cover.
I was turning 30, and still full of excitement to probe through those ghost houses, imaging the life and listening to the stories those walls told. I made a hobby of it, if I weren't terrified to encounter a creepy drug user or homeless. So I convinced my neighbor to join me and bring her super smart military trained dog. They have been trained for combat together and had both been released from the IDF only a couple of years beforehand. Originally the dog was military property, but because the bond between the dog and the human working with it under combat is so deep, they never get passed to another soldier, so they are released together to civilian life.
The dog is sweet, highly intelligent, and also capable to attack. That's why I felt safe in these abandoned spooky houses. Having the dog with us would keep us secured from any hostility. The girl would order Hebrew commands to the dog: "Texel – sit!","Texel – scan!" -  A fascinating communication system between them. Texel wags its tail upon finding scents of ammunition. She gives it a biscuit. Texel is a special name.
We have scanned deserted houses a couple of times before, but today we're going into the Templer's school. A ghost school. No one touched this school for a mere one hundred years. No reasonable person stepped in. Dangerous. The torn yard has trash, narcotics' syringes, homeless clothing, condoms and plenty of broken chairs. The structure falling apart. The stairway has no railing so we ascend while staying very close to the wall. Dangerous and stupid. We step where the structure is strongest.
She was worried that it could get cut from the sharp broken floor tiles, but still gave it an order to scan, maybe to impress me. I am. The dog runs in front of us to the second floor and scans its every corner and wall, returning to the staircase and sitting attentively. Nothing valuable found there, only chairs broken desks, streaming out of the classrooms.
The dog runs up to the third floor, which opens up to a balcony with no railing, but only a knee high step as a ledge. It hops to the ledge as I arrive up the staircase, just in time to see it scrambling and trying to stay on the ledge but finally missing its footing. It looks just like cartoons, when you see the character's legs trying to stay on some high bar but the body is floating in the air. Then Texel falls off the building. 
She arrives at the balcony. I try to keep her away from the edge. She cries hysterically, 'Where is Texel?! Texel!!'. I tell her to stay away from the edge and lean over the rail-less ledge and peek down to the yard, where I see the dog lying on its side. She shots running down the stairway. Very dangerous. I fear she would fall down as well, so I hold her tight trying to keep her calm, making sure she doesn't break free from my grip, and we slowly walked down the staircase.
She is crying and freaking out. She is calling "Texel! Shit! I can't believe it!" I hold her tighter, calming her down 'Relax! We will get Texel! Walk slowly!'. Carefully walking down 3 staircases, holding each other, we exit the building. I run to where the dog is lying. It is surrounded by dried high straw and thorns. It is weeping quietly and breathing heavily. The dog is just breathing fast, its lungs moving fast. I call the girl. The dried straw scratches our running legs. I tell her 'relax. I'm a medic. I will check it'. Then I add 'stay with the dog, I'll go call help'. I get to the part of fence where we climbed in. The whole area was blocked off by a municipality fence because of its danger. I begin climbing the fence, but realize that I don't know where to go. I yell to her 'where is the Vet?' She replies 'Go there and there - get the Vet'. I decide that we are better off if I stay with the dog and she brings the Vet.
I return to her 'ok you go get the Vet, I will stay here'. Suddenly I am alone with this dog. I feel guilt, cause it's my fault we are even in there. It is my hobby. My crazy mind that brought us up there, and now the dog is hurt because of me. So I'm petting the dog saying 'don't worry'. I'm talking to it, Instead of replying it breaths fast. I think – yalla – this is what I know how to do – to take care of a trauma. I keep talking to the dog saying 'don't worry it will be fine'. I pet the dog. Cause you are supposed to talk to a patient, you know, so I talked to the dog. Silly. I know I'm supposed to keep him conscience and focused. So I check the pulse. Then I do a survey. You're supposed to do a survey of what the situation is, just as you'd do on humans. First thing is to check a pulse and I feel a strong pulse. Then I check all the body parts, to see that there are no blood stains, to make sure it isn't losing blood. And some point I see that under the tail there is a lot of blood. It's not losing blood, but it probably got injured from the fall. The danger is that it's got internal bleeding, because of the blow to the body. It's much more dangerous when the bleeding is internal. I go over all the body parts and feel them. If I get to a broken bone I can feel it with my fingers. I went over the backbone down to the tail. Then over the legs. Leg by leg I check where it is broken. I am not a vet, I just did the equivalent procedure I'd do on a human. 
I feel something in the back. I think there's broken bone in the leg. I think. I shake its tail. I tried to see if it can move its tail. That is another thing you check, if the patient can move his limbs. I try to make it move its tail. Try and pick it up and imagined if it could wag the tail, but it couldn't. Texel is just breathing. 
She returns, 'I don't know what to do. No vet there. The only vet is in another neighborhood in Jerusalem and we have to get there or call him. I don't know. I'm really scared". I say 'let's try calling one of the vets', standing over the dog. This was already ten minutes after the fall. We get an answering machine. No one answering. Finally one vet answers the phone 'this is Friday afternoon, one o'clock, you can go to Rishon, Beit Dagan, if it's trauma – go there'. Ok thank you. We try calling the other number. They tell us we have to drive out to another neighborhood. We didn't have a car, we asked from the vet to stay available for us, because the Shabes was about to enter.
I calmly suggest 'let's first bring it to the street and take a cab to where we need to go -search for a big wooden board! - like a stretcher'. We search the area cause there was a lot of junk there. Finally I stumble over a large table top. I tried to put the dog on it, on its side, and finally somehow got it on the table and picked it up. The dog didn't respond, it just kept breathing fast. I checked it's pupils too. I'm not a doctor. They seem ok. Texsel sees. I move my finger and Texel looks at it. So it's a good sign. Somehow we carry the board over the fence. Very heavy, especially over that fence. She is very lean and petit. 
Somehow we get it to the sidewalk and I stopped a cab. I tell the driver, 'the dog is dying, can we please put him in the baggage'. He agrees and jags down the back seats. It is a station wagon taxi, so this creats enough room in the back for us to lay down the table top, and I sit on it. Before we load the dog onto the cab, just as I'd do before loading a patient onto a helicopter or an ambulance, I check his pulse and breathing for the last time.
I notice that Texel stopped breathing. Until now there were fast and shallow breaths – now, nothing. I tell the Taxi driver to wait with the loading to the cab. Oh shit. Oh shit. I take out its tongue and hold it with my finger. Texel is sort of a wolf dog. I hold it with one hand and with the other hand I seal the mouth. I put my lips to Texel's lips. I feel its teeth on my teeth. I put in two breaths. I see the chest going up. One - two. I checked the pulse in the neck, but couldn't find it.
Ok we're only gonna drive for 10 minutes in Jerusalem and there they'll have the whole trauma equipment at the Vet's and will take care of the dog. The Taxi driver helps me load the dog with the wooden platform to the buggage and I enter, on the table top, beside the dog. She sits crying in the slingshot seat, holding her cell phone and giving the driving the address instructions. 
This brings me back to the exact situation I used to have in the helicopter, in the rescue unit. You have the pilots sitting in the front, while you're dealing with the injured in the back. And it's a helicopter, you're flying, so it gets quite crazy and you don't have a seatbelt or anything. Kneeling in the back of the cab speeding through Jerusalem got intense. Shoving me up, down, and slamming into the car walls. It's quite a drive, and I'm thrown from side to side. So I check the pulse and I finally find that there is a pulse. It's partly imagination and partly true. I feel it. Almost. But I know it will be fine. I yell to her 'don't worry – it's fine- we will be there in ten minutes and the vet will take care of everything'. Then I do exactly what I am supposed to do in CPR - I give breaths.
Part of the CPR procedure is giving in such a situation two breaths to revive the patient. You know – you give two breaths every 30 seconds. So I exhale "HOOOOOO" and I count and then I give another one and I count. I keep on doing that and I see that there is a pulse. We keep speeding through Jerusalem while I was doing this. I think 7 minutes pass. I improve my technic of taking its tongue out. Because the problem is that its tongue keeps sliding in and that might cause suffocation, even when I'm not shoving in air. You know, I could see his eyes – sometimes he sees me, and moves his pupils on me, and sometimes he doesn't, and just stares into space.
I pet Texel 'it's going to be ok' and then I shout to her in the front "it's going to be ok". Then yelling to the driver 'if not that station – let's go to the other one through the bridge'. She calls and tells me that the vet station is already closed because of the Shabes, but she has a number of another vet in another neighborhood, which is just 10 minutes further. I say to the driver ' Yalla – take us to the new location'. I keep counting and every cycle, when it's time, I seal its lips, by now I've improved my technic, I look and make sure I see that the air is going in its lunges and then I check for pulse on the neck. I think I still feel the pulse. I also try something on its leg. It's not as clear, so I bring my fingers back to the neck and I feel it.
We are very close to the vet's address, and suddenly the pulse stops. By now we are 10 minutes driving. I have to make sure that the pulse stopped so I place my hand on its chest to try and feel its heart. Now, this is a big dog – at least 20 kg. A massive wolf dog. I know my CPR – so I make sure that there is no pulse and say to myself  - yalla – we will be at the vet's in another 15 minutes so I just got to get the dog there and the vet will already use electric shocks to bring back the heart pulse - Simple. I start doing full CPR. I place him differently on the board and begin CPR - 5 contractions and one breath. Ok so he's on the board – so I go 1,2,3,4,5 and give him a breath . 1,2,3,4,5 and give a breath. I feel he is getting colder. Obviously I am not telling her anything about it. I continue. And this is really tiring – it's hard work. I've been doing this for the last 20 minutes, so I am exhausted - good thing I'm in shape and still giving it breath. 
Suddenly I get worried that he won't make it. Which is very new feeling for me, cause I've never felt attached to a ... it's always technical. Just another day at work. We can talk about it. Why. Maybe because it's my fault – I caused this. Here it's my fault. Maybe because this dog belongs to my neighbor. It's also a dog I learned to like. It's not the first time we scan through deserted houses, and I admire this dog for being very smart. I can feel this dog all over my skin. I got saliva all over me and dog breath. It's grouse. It's like kissing a dog. I'm kissing a dog. I try to wipe my mouth and tongue on my shirt and ask myself what the fuck am I doing, and she is crying in the front. I have to give more heart pumps. I don't have any power left in my arm, so I lean on my side and pump the heart with my hand. You know – not the full pumps I'd want to give. The car is driving fast in the Jerusalem turns so I get tossed in the back once in a while. Slowly he becomes cold. We are going uphill. I could feel. I was pretty much on time with the breathing cycle. I was persistent. I feel the dog's soul or something leave. As if going out through the glass of the rear door of the taxi. We are just driving up that hill, while I feel it going away. I'm very determined to keep it alive so I keep pumping the heart. Giving the pumps and giving it the air. I begin crying. It's really important for me – it's like – mother fucker don't die. I'm gonna save you. I talk to it. Just like in the ER TV program. 'don't die. Don't die' while crying.
She is in the front with the taxi driver. She can't hear me crying. She asks something once in a while, getting directions on the phone or talking to the vets. It's hard directing a taxi through the chaotic streets of Jerusalem. I see her there but we are not really communicating. 
I tell the dog 'don't die. Don't die'. And I am petting it. I'm crying in between the breathing cycles. 'don't cry don’t cry we are almost there'. I give him the breaths. Slowly I feel that he is becoming cold, and what I am actually doing – is putting air into an empty body. Every time I manage to open its mouth and I feel that there is no tension in the muscles at all. You know at the beginning there was tension, but now the neck lingers back. I am actually putting air into – yes- meat. Into nothing. At the beginning of this I'd put air into his lunges and it would come out hot, but now it's coming out cold. Still, I stay on the time cycle and continue to breath air into him 1,2,3,4,5 – breath. 1,2,3,4,5 – whoooo. But it's cold meat. I hear the driver saying that we've reached the neighborhood and that they just need to make a last left turn and we've got there. It's cold meat. But by this time – I've lost it already – and I have to continue. I feel like it is a schnitzel meat. I open its eye lids and it's looking into the air. I continue 1,2,3,4,5 breath. 1,2,3,4,5 breath. 
We arrive at the vet. I exit the taxi. The vet is there outside waiting for us. I say 'hi we have a dog please check it". He goes to the door of the clinic, it's an automatic door, but it's locked and he can't seem to open it. It's stuck. He says 'I'm sorry I don't know why but I can't open the door. But you know what – there Is another vet nearby –I will take you there. It's only 3 minutes away'. I say 'can you just check the dog here. He replies that he can't do anything without the equipment. He doesn't want to touch the dog. He wants to drive his car to the other vet. We drive to the other clinic.
No. actually he doesn't want to check the dog, but I argue – "you're a vet right – so check him". The vet comes to the rear baggage of the car and checks pulse, eyes, breathing. She is crying and walking around the taxi. He opens the dog's eyes and he tells me :" look – I don't think there is much we can do". I argue with him: 'No – of course we can do. We will take the heart difibulator and shock his heart until it comes back'. He says: 'ya. But .. '. I cut him off and say 'look – I am doing CPR this way. Just tell me if it's ok?' he says yes but listen. He wants to get me off this animal. Then I convince him to just show me how to do the CPR heart pumps correctly to this dog. So he shows me,'you put your fist here and push hard into the center of the body'. He already knows that the dog is dead but he says – listen you keep on doing these pumps and I drive my car over there. Again he repeats – 'the dog is probably dead. It's shabat. Everything is closed now'. Now I am out of my mind – I say " no! we're gonna get to them. We will keep the dog alive'. He got convinced 'ok ok'. He gets into his car and leads the way to the other vet. 3 minute drive. I keep on reviving. I pump the heart correctly - I now know how to work the pressure on the heart better BUT the piece was meat. No muscle tension. I am working with meat. Remnants of a body of a dog. I know that it's cold meat. I hold on to the idea that if we get it electric shock it will revive like you see in those movies. But TACHLES the vet asked those questions – "how long since it happened?" "how high did it fall?" all the simple questions and it's been more than half an hour, with no oxygen to the brain.. I argue "no – I've been doing the CPR more than half an hour so I got the oxygen in there". Every one knows that if you get the patience in the first hour to the ER there is a good chance to save him. Obviously this vet knows that there was some truth to it.
We get to the second clinic. It's a Russian woman. We carry the wooden board in. She checks the dog and says that there is nothing to do. I protest, 'let's give it electric shock'. She explains that they don't even have that equipment there. There is nothing to do. The girl is crying. We are sent to the waiting room to drink water and relax and we need to tell the vets what to do with the body. One of the vets offers to take us to a dog cemetery. It costs only 400 shekels. 
I urge to the toilets to my wash my mouth. I scrub my tongue and lips with soap. I will have that dog breath for the next couple of days on me. All the saliva over me. I finally drink some water. The girl calls her mother. The vet tresses – it is shabat and they have to close and we should tell them what to do with body.
********
Remembering what happened afterwards:
********************

Somehow the first vet – said that he would help us and show us where we can bury it for free, near his village out in nature.
Somehow I got a cab back home. I got my parents' car and drove to my school. At the time we had a Becket production, which had a shovel as part of the villagers' stage design, so I took it. A big farmer's shovel.  My school was empty because it was Shabat evening. We drove with the dog to his place in the village. We put the dog in my baggage, wrapped in white bed sheets that I brought. 
On a hill 10 minutes out of Jerusalem, near the curve, down a slope – that's where we should bury the dog. I went out of the car down the slope in the middle of nowhere with the shovel. I tried to find a place where I could dig. It was hard. I could only scrap a few centimeters into the ground. I brought the dog down the slope, carrying it on my back like a bag of potatoes. Or like you'd carry a wounded soldier. Grabbed two legs in each of my hands and swung it up.
Not finding proper burring soil was defeating.  She was very sad. She cried a lot. I was very tired. There was no way I could carry the dog back up to the car to find another burring location. This was it. This is where we're gonna bury it. So I just got more rocks I picked up on the slope and placed them around the body and on him. Still many spots of fur could be seen through. She said a few words while pointing the flashlight to the pile of rocks. I said a few words. Then we got up back to the car.
The drive back was quiet. She was in total shock. I offered her to come to my parents' for Friday dinner. My sister talked to her. When she saw my parents' dog "Y" it broke her heart all over.
That's it. That's the whole story.
It wasn't that kind of an outstanding emotional event if it not for my own history. After many years of treating patients or dying people or death or almost dying, I never ever really cared about any of those human beings. It really didn't matter if he or she were alive or not. It was very technical for me. You could have placed a sandbag and it would be exactly the same process for me. Just pass it from A to B. very simple. Not any emotion involved. I didn't remember the names or anything. Connection or nothing.
This was the first time I had some kind of connection. I really wanted for Texel to make it through. And I fought for him. You know how in the movies you see how the doctors are fighting for the patient's life – in reality – no one fights for a patient. When he's dead he's dead. 
This was the first time I had fought. More than half an hour CPR sitting in a car. I passed through some kind of emotional memory and I re-enacted all those rescues in which I did not care about those patients. It was the first time I really cared. I cried and I talked to it and I petted it. You know - it's only a dog, but I kept talking to it 'it's gonna be ok'. Just me and him talking. 'you'll be ok you'll be ok' I really did all I can, which would never happen with a humans.
Act V:

Poem:
I am landing from gusts and storms
Soon on ground, will walk my way across 
Mountains and oceans
Not gonna detain myself anymore. Unleashed mind’s prison shackles.


Scene Y:
The recent days in Gaza are warm. That means bombs flying everywhere. When one comes near my location, a serene is sounded, the same exact siren sounded at memorial days.
Now directed to walking calmly to the designated shelter, we have up to ninety seconds to get into a shelter, which is enough time to save the material on the computer, wear shoes and decent cloths and elegantly reach safety.
In the shelter I sit, waiting for the bomb to hit or be hit down in the air and detonate above my head, giving off a shattering wave that causes the buildings to wobble.
This wait is difficult, for I am powerless, just waiting and calculating my odds. I know I am in strength, but my body - wants to jump out, to run, to fight back, to reach my mark where I carry out my duty of protecting the country. 
I arrive wearing only under wear to the staircase of the building. There are already some neighbors there. Some are wearing robes, some bare foot, some only in their shorts. 
Fat Neighbor: You need to stand away from the glass. There. If a bomb falls in the middle of the street, the blast will go this direction, and will blow the glass that direction. So keep away at least four meters. Now if the ceiling of this building collapses, all this place here will be a sure crashing ground for the debris, and best to stand right here under the arc of this doorway, so make sure to have some water installed, and until the rescue team evacuates the pieces you'll be fine. 
Scene P:
I hear a raising siren. I look outside the window, but no truck is arriving, no plane flying low, no motorcycle accelerating and this time it is definitely a real city siren. I get up and move calmly towards the shelter. I know I should have almost 30 seconds until the first missile hits.
In the shelter I cover the glass window – with a towel. Years have prepared me for these moments and now my reaction feels everyday ordinary. 
Now I feel sleepy. Is this my body's reaction? I am non responsive. Is this the result of the pills I take or is it my physic reacting to fright.

Scene Q:
Driving in my first car to Tel Aviv, on the radio Dylan's Mr. Tambourine Man is interrupted by a reporter who calmly says "Siren in Rehovot". Shit I am now passing right near Rehovot.
I turn off the AC and open the window to hear sirens echoing throughout the city. I stop the car on the side of the highway. Other cars do the same. Luckily there is a concrete rain collection ditch on the side of the road. I jump in, and lay low covering my head with my arms. I burst into tears as I peek and see right above me in the sky, a missile exploding in the air, hit by the Israeli missile defense system. I am totally shattered.
 If this would have been a firework demonstration, I could cheer impressed by the sound effects and precision, but that capability of turning the fright into a challenging cinematic excitement is no longer an option. Instead there is the real truth of fearing death. I am imagining a missile hitting and being blown up, tossed in the air.
Laying in that ditch beside the car, crying hysterically like a baby, terrified of the bombs exploding above me in the air, I am not fit for any activity. 




 


The End


